{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18737"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18737"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.61,0.37,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9918"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26560"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG), also known as 2,3-diphosphoglyceric acid (2,3-DPG), is an important molecule produced by red blood cells that influences oxygen transport.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Catalyses haemoglobin synthesis","Stimulates red blood cell production","Decreases haemoglobin oxygen affinity","Increases haemoglobin oxygen affinity","Facilitates carbon dioxide transport"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of 2,3-BPG is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edecrease haemoglobin oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E. By binding to the beta chains of deoxyhaemoglobin, 2,3-BPG stabilises the low-affinity state, making it more difficult for oxygen to bind. This right-shifts the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve and facilitates oxygen release to tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases haemoglobin oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E - This would impair oxygen release to tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates red blood cell production\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of erythropoietin, not 2,3-BPG\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatalyses haemoglobin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - 2,3-BPG does not participate in haemoglobin production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates carbon dioxide transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Carbon dioxide transport primarily involves carbonic anhydrase and the chloride shift\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2,3-BPG levels increase during chronic hypoxia as an adaptive mechanism to enhance oxygen delivery to tissues. It is produced in red blood cells as a byproduct of glycolysis through the Rapoport-Luebering shunt.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG) binds to haemoglobin and reduces its oxygen affinity, facilitating oxygen release to tissues.","2,3-BPG levels increase during chronic hypoxia as an adaptation to improve oxygen delivery.","Red blood cells produce 2,3-BPG as a byproduct of glycolysis via the Rapoport-Luebering shunt."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18737"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T15:45:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T20:14:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11469"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13